# Plan: Remove the v1 `postmarks` app via a full `common` migration history reset

## Context

The legacy v1 Django app `backend/postmarks/` is dead weight that actively breaks
the project: its migration graph cannot be rendered (`InvalidBasesError`), so a
normal `manage.py test` / fresh `migrate` / test-DB build fails. The only current
workaround is `backend/woco/test_settings_nomig.py`, which skips migrations.

Why it's broken: `postmarks/migrations/0001_initial` (+0002/0003) create PROXY
models (`Listing`, `Location`, `CatalogRequest`, ...) whose bases
(`common.postmark`, `common.administrativeunit`, ...) were deleted during the
v1->v2 unification, leaving dangling bases in the final migration state. The cruft
is not isolated to `postmarks`: six `common` migrations have OPERATION-level
references to postmarks proxies (`to='postmarks.location'`), and `common`'s own
77-migration history is full of v1 junk.

Decision (confirmed): **full history reset** of `common` into a single fresh
`0001_initial` generated from current v2 models, plus deletion of the `postmarks`
app. Dev and staging both have the history applied and are reconciled with
`--fake-initial`.

User constraints (confirmed):
- No backups needed.
- Data is brought in fresh via an existing import pipeline; that pipeline MUST
  keep working.
- User auth/role data is saved separately, so seed-data migrations do NOT need to
  be ported.

Why the import pipeline is safe: this reset is SCHEMA-NEUTRAL. It deletes/rewrites
only migration-history records (`django_migrations` rows + the migration .py
files); it never alters, drops, or recreates a live table during the in-place
reconcile (`--fake-initial`). The Phase 2 schema-diff gate proves the regenerated
`0001_initial` produces a byte-identical schema, so anything reading/writing the
tables (the import pipeline included) is unaffected.

Outcome: clean migration history, zero v1 cruft; `manage.py migrate`,
`makemigrations --check`, and `manage.py test common.tests` all work with no
workaround; `postmarks` and `test_settings_nomig.py` are gone.

## Key facts established during research

- `postmarks` creates ZERO real tables (all proxies). Entire DB footprint = 8 rows
  in `django_migrations`; no tables, no `django_content_type` rows.
- Six `common` migrations reference postmarks. Operation-level (the reason a
  surgical excise fails): `0012`, `0013`, `0034` (`to='postmarks.location'`).
  Dependency/RunSQL-only: `0038`, `0044`, `0045`.
- No Python imports `postmarks`; all frontend "postmarks" hits are the domain word.
  Only `common` is entangled; no other app depends on postmarks.
- Live dev DB has ORPHAN CamelCase tables `AdministrativeUnits`,
  `AdministrativeUnitIdentities`, `AdministrativeUnitResponsibilities`: `0045`'s
  `DROP TABLE IF EXISTS common_administrativeunit*` used the wrong (snake_case)
  names and no-op'd. Not in v2 models -> drop them.
- No migration seeds `Color` id=1 (the `Marking.color default=1` assumes it as
  data). Not ported (comes from the import pipeline). See "Known test assumption".

