## Phase 1 -- File/code changes

1. Delete every file under `backend/common/migrations/` EXCEPT `__init__.py`.
2. Delete the entire `backend/postmarks/` directory.
3. `backend/woco/settings.py`: remove the `"postmarks.apps.PostmarksConfig"`
   INSTALLED_APPS entry and its explanatory comment (lines ~72-75).
4. Delete `backend/woco/test_settings_nomig.py`.

## Phase 2 -- Generate the fresh history + prove it is schema-neutral

5. From backend cwd: `python manage.py makemigrations common`
   -> clean `common/migrations/0001_initial.py` (one, or a small few, generated
   files) from current v2 models. The broken graph is gone, so this succeeds.
   Confirm NO `postmarks` reference and none of the deleted v1 models
   (`Postmark`, `AdministrativeUnit*`, `Location*`, `Listing*`). (`Postcover` IS a
   current model -- expected.)
6. Capture the live schema reference (structure only) for the diff gate:
   `mysqldump --defaults-extra-file=.../mysql.cnf --no-data --skip-comments worldcovers > /tmp/schema_dev_before.sql`
   (and have the user produce `/tmp/schema_staging_before.sql` -- dev/staging may
   have drifted differently).
7. Build a SCRATCH DB purely from the new migrations and verify it renders:
   `mysql ... -e "DROP DATABASE IF EXISTS wc_scratch; CREATE DATABASE wc_scratch;"`
   then `DB_NAME=wc_scratch python manage.py migrate` (must finish with NO
   `InvalidBasesError`).
8. Dump scratch schema `--no-data` and diff vs `/tmp/schema_dev_before.sql` (and
   the staging snapshot). Normalize (sort, strip AUTO_INCREMENT/comments) first.
   - Expected legitimate diff: live DBs have the 3 orphan `AdministrativeUnit*`
     tables not present in the scratch schema -> Phase 3 drop targets.
   - ANY other structural difference is real drift: fix the new initial or add a
     corrective migration BEFORE faking. Do not proceed to Phase 3 until the only
     diffs are the known orphan tables. This gate is what guarantees the import
     pipeline still sees an identical schema.
   - Drop `wc_scratch` when satisfied.

## Phase 3 -- Reconcile dev, then staging (in-place, non-destructive to data)

9. Dev: clear old recorded history for the reset apps only, then fake the new one:
   - `mysql ... worldcovers -e "DELETE FROM django_migrations WHERE app IN ('common','postmarks');"`
   - `python manage.py migrate common --fake-initial`
   - confirm `python manage.py showmigrations common` shows `0001_initial [X]`.
10. Drop the orphan v1 tables surfaced in Phase 2 (adjust set to the diff result):
    ``mysql ... worldcovers -e "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS `AdministrativeUnitIdentities`,`AdministrativeUnitResponsibilities`,`AdministrativeUnits`;"``
11. Staging (user runs same recipe): run the Phase 2 diff against the staging
    snapshot to confirm its orphan set, then `DELETE FROM django_migrations ...`,
    `migrate common --fake-initial`, and drop staging's confirmed orphan tables.
    (Alternative, since data is re-imported fresh: drop+`migrate`+re-import instead
    of `--fake-initial`. Either yields the same clean state.)

## Phase 4 -- End-to-end verification (no workaround)

12. From backend cwd, dev DB:
    - `python manage.py check` -> 0 issues.
    - `python manage.py makemigrations --check --dry-run` -> exit 0 (new initial
      fully captures current models).
    - `python manage.py migrate` -> "No migrations to apply."
    - Fresh test-DB build via the NORMAL command (no `--settings` workaround):
      `python manage.py test common.tests -v 2`.

### Known test assumption (Color id=1)
The test DB is built from the schema-only new initial, so it has no `Color` rows.
`test_marking_dispatch_still_returns_marking` relies on `Marking.color default=1`
=> needs a `Color` id=1 (a pre-existing data assumption, not introduced by this
reset; it is also absent on any bare DB today). Resolve at execution by the lightest
option: if the suite must be green on a bare DB, seed `Color` id=1 in that test's
fixture/`setUp`; otherwise leave it -- the import pipeline supplies colors on real
DBs. Do NOT add a seed migration (per user: auth/data come from the pipeline).

## Phase 5 -- Team / CI / cross-branch coordination (flag, not code)

13. Other active branches carry the OLD `common` migrations + the `postmarks` app
    and must rebase onto the reset; any CI job that builds a DB from migrations
    should be re-run. Note in the PR description.

## Critical files

- `backend/postmarks/` (delete entire dir)
- `backend/common/migrations/*` (delete all except `__init__.py`; regenerate)
- `backend/woco/settings.py` (remove postmarks from INSTALLED_APPS)
- `backend/woco/test_settings_nomig.py` (delete)
- `backend/common/models.py` (read-only reference for the generated initial)

## Risks and mitigations

- Hidden schema drift faked over: mitigated by the Phase 2 scratch-DB schema-diff
  gate (do not fake until only the known orphan-table diffs remain), run against
  BOTH dev and staging snapshots. This is also the import-pipeline safety guarantee.
- Orphan-table drops: target only v1 tables absent from v2 models, confirmed by the
  diff -- no live v2 data touched.
- No backups by request: acceptable because the in-place reconcile is fake-only
  (no schema mutation) and data is re-importable.
- Cross-environment/branch mismatch: dev+staging reconciled here; branches/CI
  flagged in Phase 5.

